      "soil_ph": "Circumneutral (pH 6.8-7.2)",
      "soil_description": "Sandy, loamy, clay, and limestone soils. Moist, well-drained, woodland soils best.",
      "native_distribution": "Central Texas east to Florida and Cuba, north to Arkansas and South Carolina, south through Mexico to the Yucatan and Chiapas. Other varieties of the species continue south through Central America to South America.",
      "native_habitat": "Found along streams, on the edges of woods, and on wooded limestone slopes and ledges.",
      "attracts": "Birds , Butterflies , Hummingbirds",
      "wildlife": "Nectar-hummingbirds, Nectar-butterflies, Nectar-moths, Nectar-insects, Fruit-birds, Fruit-mammals",
      "ornamental_use": "Turk's Cap is a good ornamental for shady sites. Cultivars have been selected for white blooms and variegated foliage.",
      "food_use": "The fruit is edible either raw or cooked, tasting rather like apple, hence its Spanish name, Manzanilla (Little Apple).",
      "description": "Turk's Cap will germinate promptly from fresh, untreated seeds planted outside after danger of frost is past. Germination of Turk's Cap is inhibited by cold temperatures. Cover the seeds no deeper than 1/4 - 1/2 inches. Turk's Cap is also propagated easily from softwood cuttings. These cuttings should be 4 to 6 inches long with leaves from the bottom halves removed and treated with rooting hormone. Large clumps of Turk's Cap may easily be separated in early spring and transplanted to a new site. Be sure to water well.",
      "seed_collection": "Collect the seeds as soon as the fruit turns ripe. Spread the fruit on screens to dry and separate. After a few days, the pulp will shrivel and may easily be rubbed off the seeds.",
      "seed_treatment": "After thoroughly drying, dust the seeds with an insecticide and store in ventilated containers at room temperature. Seeds stored for long periods of time should be refrigerated in sealed containers.",
      "maintenance": "To keep at a desirable height and shape, prune back after a couple years. To keep it waist-high in the Southeast, cut it back to 5 inches after the last frost. Can be kept cut back to give the appearance of a ground cover, though it doesn't spread by either rhizomes or stolons but by layering. Will bloom even when cut short.",
